[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 5...Nxd4?!"]
[Black "Model Game #1: 6...Nxe5?! usually loses material!"]
[Result "*"]

{ Ayats Llobera, G  (2157)  - Riera Morilla  (2133) } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bc4 { The Bishop is on the most aggressive square and pressures f7. } 3... Bc5
{ This move is played the most often. } 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ We don't play the quiet 5. d3! This is a very forcing move, which gives us the initiative. }
5... Nxd4
{ Even this natural move falls into a trap. I've often had this position in blitz games. }
6. Nxe5 O-O
{ In practice this will be the move Black plays. Because he is out of his book, he already has big problems. }
7. Be3 { This pin wins material straight out of the opening. } 7... Ne6
{ Otherwise we just take on d4. } 8. Bxe6 fxe6
{ This is an interesting approach, which gives White a won position.  8...Bxe3  is covered in the theoretical section. }
9. Bxc5 d6 { Because of the pin, this fork loses strength. } 10. Ba3 dxe5 11.
Bxf8 Qxf8 12. Nc3 { White is simply up an exchange. } 12... b6
{ Black wants to pressure the e4-pawn. } 13. Qd3
{ White over-defends e4 and makes space for his rooks. } 13... a5 14. Qg3
{ Attacking the weak e5 pawn. } 14... Qc5 15. a4
{ Gaining space and strengthening the b5-square. } 15... Bb7 16. Rfe1
{ 16.Rad1!?  was even stronger, creating pressure on the d-file. e4 can't be taken because of  16...Nxe4  17.Nxe4  Bxe4  18.Rd7  . }
16... Rf8 17. h3 Nh5 18. Qe3
{ White is an exchange up and would love to exchange queens. } 18... Qe7 19.
Ne2 { Here too  19.Rad1  was much stronger. } 19... Qh4 20. Ng3
{ White's king is safe. } 20... Nf6 21. Qb3
{ The e6 pawn is stuck and a great target. } 21... Re8 22. Rad1
{ Now every white piece is active. You should always try to maximize your activity! }
22... g5 { Weakening her king. } 23. Nf5
{ Because of the pin, the white knight finds a nice home. } 23... Qh5 24. g4
{ This weakening wasn't necessary, but it is winning, too. } 24... Qg6 25. Rd8
{ This rook can't be taken because of  25...Rxd8  26.Ne7+  . } 25... Kf8
{ After this move, Black's position falls apart very quickly. } 26. Qxe6 Nxe4
27. Qe7+
{ With checkmate in two moves. This game was a very nice example for the invisible danger that comes with the Max-Lange-Gambit. The black player had a 2100+ rating and couldn't find a way to leave the opening without getting a losing position. I am sure that you will find yourself very often in a won game after the opening if you learn the following lines well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 5...Nxd4?!"]
[Black "Model Game #2: Prevent your opponent's development!"]
[Result "*"]

{ Tyomkin, D  (2498)  - Noritsyn, N  (2175) } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Bishop is on the most aggressive square and pressures f7. } 3... Bc5
{ This move is played the most often. } 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ We don't play the quiet 5. d3! This is a very forcing move, which gives us the initiative. }
5... Nxd4
{ Even this natural move falls into a trap. I've often had this position in blitz games. }
6. Nxe5 Ne6
{ In this game Black plays the more precise move 6... Ne6, after which White is still clearly better. }
7. Bxe6 fxe6
{ Taking with the d-pawn was not an option:  7...dxe6?  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  9.Nxf7++- }
8. Nd3 { The best move, as we will discuss in the theoretical part. } 8... Be7
{ This is the main alternative to  8...Bb6  .  The bishop was safer on e7, but more passive. }
9. e5
{ The right move, seizing more space and creating a dangerous initiative. }
9... Nd5 10. Qh5+
{ In our repertoire I decided to recommend the move  10.Qf3  directly instead of the intermediate move 10. Qh5+ because of one major drawback, explained in the note to Black's 11th move. }
10... g6 11. Qf3 { We have reached a similar position to our repertoire. }
11... d6
{ This is not the best defense. Black should have played   11...Rf8  and after  12.Qh3  the defensive move  12...Rf7  would have been possible. This is a downside of provoking 10.g6. }
12. Bh6 { A nice square for the bishop. } 12... Bd7 13. Qh3 Rg8
{ The wrong choice. The best defense was  13...Bf8  , but it is easy to see that White is better. }
14. Nd2 { Heading for e4. } 14... Bg5 15. Ne4 Bxh6 16. Qxh6
{ White has a won position. There is no good way to defend against c4 followed by Nf6+. }
16... Qe7 17. c4 Nb6 18. Nf6+ { Picking up the exchange. } 18... Kf7 19. Nxg8
Kxg8 20. b3 { With a very easy win for White. } 20... Rf8 21. exd6 cxd6 22. Qe3
Rf5 23. a4 Rh5 24. Rfe1 e5 25. a5 Nc8 26. Nf4 Rf5 27. Nd5 Qf8 28. Rad1 Bc6 29.
Nb4 Be8 30. c5 dxc5 31. Rd8 Ne7 32. Qxc5 e4 33. Qc4+ Kh8 34. Qxe4
{ This game was a great example of the strength of White's initiative in this opening. It's a common strategy to prevent Black from castling in these lines, which leads to a brutal attack in most cases. It's important to emphasize that the 5... Nxd4?! line is one of Black's weakest options. }
*

