1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Bishop is on the most aggressive square and pressures f7. } 3... Bc5
{ This move is played most often. } 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ We don't play d3! This is a really forcing move, which gives us the initiative. }
5... Nxd4
{ Even this natural move falls into a trap. I had this position often in blitz games. }
6. Nxe5 Ne6 { This is a try to limit the damage. } 7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. Nd3 Be7
{ This retreat looks like a safer option because the bishop isn't exposed on e7, but it's also very passive. }
9. e5 Nd5 10. Qf3
{ It will be very hard for Black to finish his development. The following line is just an example of White outplaying his opponent. }
10... d6 11. c4 { Gaining more space without losing time. } 11... Nb6 12. b3
Bd7 13. Bb2 Bc6 14. Qh5+ g6 15. Qh6
{ We have gained serious initiative despite the even material. } *

