1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Bishop is on the most aggressive square and pressures f7. } 3... Bc5
{ This move is played most often. } 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ We don't play d3! This is a real forcing move, which gives us the initiative. }
5... Nxd4
{ Even this natural move falls into a trap. I had this position often in blitz games. }
6. Nxe5 Qe7
{ This might be the best defense, after which White is still clearly better. }
7. Bxf7+ Kf8 8. Nd3
{ This is an important move to remember, White has to bring his pieces back in his camp safely. }
8... d6 { We will come to the more forcing moves later. } 9. Nxc5 dxc5 10. Bc4
Qxe4 11. Bd3
{ We always want to play for initiative! Here White's initiative is decisive, for example: }
11... Qc6 12. c3 Ne6 13. Re1 Bd7 14. Na3
{ On first sight Black has chances to survive, but White has plans of ♘c4-♘e5, f4-f5 and Black's king is in danger. }
