[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. 5...exd4"]
[Black "Model Game #3: Not knowing theory is deadly for Black."]
[Result "*"]

{ Lukasiewicz, K  (2218)  - Borkowski, F  (2278) } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4 exd4
{ This natural move leads to a very uncomfortable game for the black player. White's initiative is just stunning! }
6. e5 d5 { The only good move. } 7. exf6
{ We enter a forced line in which it is very hard for Black to survive. } 7...
dxc4 8. fxg7 Rg8 9. Bg5
{ This is the move! Black has to find unexpected moves. I'm sure that very few players know the theory in this rare gambit. }
9... Qd5 { This natural move already loses. I meet it very often in Blitz. }
10. Nc3 { This is a nice opportunity enabled by the pin. } 10... Qf5
{ ♘b5 and ♘e4 make other squares for the queen unattractive. } 11. Re1+
{ 11.Re1+   and  11.Ne4  just transpose to eachother. } 11... Be6 12. Ne4
{ White wins the exchange. Note that  12...Be7  makes things even worse after  13.Bxe7  Kxe7  14.Nxd4  . }
12... Rxg7 13. Nh4 { The queen is trapped.  13...Qe5  runs into  14.Nef6+  . }
13... Rxg5 14. Nxf5 Rxf5 15. g4 { White will win without any problems. } 15...
Rf4 { This is just the final blunder by the IM with the black pieces. } 16.
Nxc5 O-O-O 17. Rxe6
{ A very nice game ! You can see that even some IMs or other very strong players don't know the theory in this opening. In this case it just ended in a disaster for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. 5...exd4"]
[Black "Model Game #4: After 5...exd4, even theoretical lines end in a tough position for Black."]
[Result "*"]

{ Kulon, K  (2359)  - Walkusz, W  (2115) } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4
{ This will just transpose to our repertoire. } 4... exd4 5. O-O Bc5
{ Now we have transposed. } 6. e5 d5 { The only good move. } 7. exf6
{ We enter a forced line, in which it is very hard for Black, to survive. }
7... dxc4 8. fxg7 Rg8 9. Bg5
{ This is the move! Black has to find unexpected moves. Im sure, that less players know the theory in this rare gambit. }
9... Be7 { This is the best move. } 10. Bxe7 Kxe7
{ It will be painful for your opponent to play this move. } 11. Re1+ Be6
{ Black knew very well that to do. Theoretically he is near equality, but practically White will have the much easier game as shown in this game which was won by White in 9 moves. }
12. Re4 { Attacking d4. } 12... Rxg7 { Is inaccurate. Better was  12...d3  . }
13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Rxd4 { We play the same way, see the theoretical section. }
14... Qg8
{ This is the first deviation from our line. Qe8 seems more precise. } 15. g3
{ Our king is in no danger and we have considerable activity, which is very worthy. }
15... Rd8 16. Nc3
{ That's right. Just finishing the development is often the best choice. White is much better here. A plan might be   17.Rxd8  Qxd8  18.Qf3  with the idea of Ne4, Rd1 and Qxb7. }
16... Rg4 { Looks reasonable, but makes things worse for Black. } 17. Nd5+
{ A nice tactical hit. With his pieces much better placed, it's logical, that the tactical chances are on the White side. }
17... Kf8
{ This loses very quickly. Better was   17...Bxd5  , but after exchanging the rooks on d5, b7 is hanging and Re1 brings the winning attack. }
18. Nf4
{ And White has completely won. After   18...Rxd4  19.Qxd4  Black has no chance to survive due to Qf6 and Rd1-d8 threats. }
18... Ke7 19. Nxe6
{ Just wins material and the game. This was a great example of the difficulty in surviving the opening as Black, even after knowing the mainlines. This 2100+ rated player wasn't able to. }
*

