[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. 5...Bxd4"]
[Black "Model Game #5: Even strong titled players don't know every trap!"]
[Result "*"]

{ Honfi, K  (2070)  - Eismont, O  (2410) } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4.
O-O Nf6 5. d4 Bxd4
{ This is the best move, if Black knows what to do, he will equalize but it won't be easy at all, White will obtain the initiative for a long time and its very hard for a non-titled player to survive against a prepared Max Lange Gambit player. Usually we will always regain our pawn. }
6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Bg5
{ The main move is  7.f4  , but this tricky move leaves the common theory and is full of tricks. You have to know that the position is objectively about equal, but Black has to know what he does. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 { Holding the pin. } 8... g5
{ Black has fallen into a cruel trap. } 9. f4
{ The IM didn't know this line, he must have been very shocked by  9.f4! } 9...
Ne6 { Is not the best defense, as you will see in the theoretical part. } 10.
Bxe6 { This strong capture leads to a winning position. } 10... dxe6
{ fxe6 is even worse, it runs into fxg5 and with it black's camp will just be in ruins. }
11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. fxg5 { It looks bad for Black. } 12... Nxe4
{ The only move. } 13. g6+
{ This is a very important check, after which f7 is falling and with it tho whole black ruin. }
13... Ng5 14. Rxf7 { With the deadly threat of g7. } 14... Ke8 15. Bxg5 hxg5
16. Nc3 { Nb5, Ne4 and Raf1 are too strong threats, Black can't do anything. }
16... Rg8 17. Nb5 Rxg6 18. Raf1
{ With checkmate following. Black's pieces are totally uncoordinated. } 18...
Kd8 19. Nxc7
{ Rh7 was mate in 7 but Nxc7 is also fine. It's surprising, but the g5-blunder happens quite often, even to titled players. In this game a 2400+ rated player lost very quick against a 2070 player, who knew what to do. I'm sure you will win some games with this tactic, I also did. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. 5...Bxd4"]
[Black "Model Game #6: Play our typical plans against unknown moves."]
[Result "*"]

{ Neubauer, M  (2295)  - Gyimesi, Z  (2390) } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4.
O-O Nf6 5. d4 Bxd4
{ This is the best move, if Black knows what to do, he will equalize but it won't be easy at all, White will obtain the initiative for a long time and its very hard for a non-titled player to survive against a prepared Max Lange Gambit player. Usually we will always regain our pawn. }
6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Bg5
{ The main move is 7. f4, but this tricky move leaves the common theory and is full of tricks. You have to know that the position is objectively about equal, but Black has to know what he does. }
7... c6
{ This move is absolutely uncommon. White surely didn't know what theory recommends here. But he just played the typical plans like f4 or attacking the king and managed it, to win against an oponent with a rating of almost 2400. }
8. f4 { Our basic breakthrough. } 8... Qb6 { Black tries to scare with Qb6. }
9. fxe5
{ This move requires a little bit of calculation, but White ends up fine. }
9... Ne6+ { That's the best move. } 10. Kh1 { The king is safe on h1. } 10...
Nxe4 { 10...Nxg5  would have given White a clear advantage after  11.exf6  . }
11. Bh4 { White just plays logical moves. } 11... O-O
{ Let's take a look at this position. White has the f-file, the two bishops and a strong central pawn. Black has the better pawn structure and strong nights on e6 and e4. }
12. Bxe6 { Exchanges the best defender of the black king. } 12... dxe6 13. Nc3
{ White tries to exchange the nights. You can say: 'His pawn structure is ruined after that', and you would be right. But that is just a static advantage, so it's long-term related, you will feel the weakness in an endgame. Just compare the two bishops and the kings after  13...Nxc3  .  The engine gives a clear advantage to White after 13. Nc3. }
13... Qb4 { Trying to have the queen activated after an exchange on e4. } 14.
Qh5 { That's right ! White's attack is already very dangerous. } 14... Nxc3 15.
bxc3 Qc5
{ Taking on c3 was impossible because of   15...Qxc3  16.Rad1  with a huge initiative. There are threats like Rd8 or Bf6. f7 will get very weak. }
16. Qg4 { Threatening Bf6. } 16... Kh8 17. Rad1
{ The game is won now, as demonstrated in the following moves. } 17... b6 18.
Bf6 { with checkmate in 4 moves. } 18... gxf6 19. exf6 Rg8
{ Maybe Black overlooked the winning tactic. } 20. Rd8
{ A nice finish. White played without theoretical knowledge against Black's preperation and was able to win quickly with our typical plans. Be sure you understand them well ! }
*

