[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Bishop is on the most aggressive square and pressures f7. } 3... Bc5
{ This move is played most often. } 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ We don't play d3! This is a real forcing move, which gives us the initiative. }
5... Bxd4
{ This is the best move, if Black knows what to do, he will equalize but it won't be easy at all, White will obtain the initiative for a long time and its very hard for a non-titled player to survive against a prepared Max Lange Gambit player. Usually we will always regain our pawn. }
6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Bg5
{ The main move is  7.f4  , but this tricky move leaves the common theory and is full of tricks. You have to know that the position is objectively about equal, but Black has to know what he to do. }
7... d6 8. f4
{ This is our standard break, which saves us the initiative. Usually we will regain the sacrificed pawn. }
8... Be6 { We are following the mainline of the Max Lange Gambit. } 9. Na3
{ On Be6 we usually play Na3 which develops a piece and speeds up the development of the a1-rook. }
9... Qe7
{ You will meet this flexible move very often. It's a typical housekeeping move, that has the additional idea of playing Qc5 at some point after the exchange on e5. }
10. fxe5
{ At some point, we should take on e5, to create a weakness and activate our pieces. }
10... dxe5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. c3
{ In these structure, we often kick the knight away with c3. Now c2 is available for ♘a3. A typical route would be Na3-c2-e3-e5/f5. }
12... Nc6 13. Qf3 { Pressuring f6 } 13... O-O-O { Giving up f6 was necessary. }
14. Qxf6 Qxf6 15. Rxf6 Rd2
{ This might look dangerous, but White is successfully able to cover the second row, by playing Rf2. }
16. Rf2 Rhd8 17. Raf1
{ With Nc4 coming. The position is about equal. Maybe white is even slightly better  (+0,20)  . }
*

